04897nam a22005655i 9780773559875DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2020416073  a97807735598757 a10.1515/97807735598752doi  a(DE-B1597)654575  a(OCoLC)1111735931  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA00aBX1533.C68bC43 2019 4aBX4705.C2385b.C437 2019 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a282.0922231 aChapman-Adisho, Annette, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPatriot and Priest :bJean-Baptiste Volfius and the Constitutional Church in the Côte-d'Or /cAnnette Chapman-Adisho. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b8 b&w images, 4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Religion ;v28500tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tCreating a Diocese: The Case of Dijon -- t1789: The Diocese of Dijon's Clergy in a Revolutionary Year -- tA Bishop for the Côte-d'Or -- tOrganizing the Constitutional Church in the Côte-d'Or -- tThe First Terror against the Clergy, 1792 -- tBattling Fanaticism: Dechristianization in the Côte-d'Or -- tThe Campaign for Religious Liberty and Establishing the Gallican Church -- tReligious Pluralism and the Early Directory, 1795–1797 -- tTargeting Fanaticism and Cultivating Citizens -- tReviving Conciliarism in the Gallican Church: National Councils and the Synod of the Côte-d'Or -- tConclusion -- tEpilogue -- tCareers of Eleven Constitutional Clergy Elected in the District of Arnay-le-Duc in March 1791 -- tAbbé Reinert's Research on the Ecclesiastical Oath of 1791 in the Côte-d'Or -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1790, the French revolutionary government reformed the Catholic Church and demanded that clerics swear an oath of allegiance to the nation and its vision for French Catholicism. Although half of France's parish clergy refused to accept the state-sponsored reforms, others became embroiled in this decade-long ecclesiastical experiment. This included Jean-Baptiste Volfius, a patriot, priest, and professor who embraced the changes in France and believed in the revolution's potential to create a purer church. Patriot and Priest presents a social and intellectual history of the French constitutional church in the Côte-d'Or and the career of Volfius, who became its bishop in 1791, as he struggled to create and run the church. Annette Chapman-Adisho addresses the daily experience of the constitutional clergy over the course of ten years, exploring the interactions between priests and local and national authorities, the response of the laity to the divisions in the French Catholic Church, the evolution of these issues over time, and the eventual reconciliation of the clergy following the Napoleonic Concordat with Pope Pius VII in 1801. Using a rich collection of archival sources, this book demonstrates that although the constitutional church was ultimately a failed project, its legacy had a lasting impact on the catholic Church in France. Tracing the social, political, and theological history of this reform effort, Patriot and Priest offers new insights into the French Revolution and its impact on French Catholicism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCatholic ChurchzFrancexClergyvBiography. 0aChurch and statezFrancezCôte-d'OrxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311127268908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019z97831112749